## ğŸ§  The Golden Rule (Coverage)

> **Use `intersect` only when the bins come from the *same signal/value space*.**
> **If one signal is just a condition â†’ use `iff`.**

---

## âœ… When `intersect` is CORRECT

### Same signal, different bin subsets

```systemverilog
coverpoint paddr {
  bins low  = {[0   : 1023]};
  bins mid  = {[1024: 2047]};
  bins even = {[0:4095]} with (item % 2 == 0);
}

bins low_even =
  binsof(paddr.low) intersect binsof(paddr.even);
```

âœ” Same signal: `paddr`
âœ” Same value space
âœ” Logical AND on address values

---

### Transitions on the same signal

```systemverilog
coverpoint psel {
  bins rise = (0 => 1);
  bins fall = (1 => 0);
}

bins rise_only =
  binsof(psel.rise) intersect binsof(psel);
```

âœ” Same signal
âœ” Same timeline

---

## âŒ When `intersect` is WRONG

### Different signals (your APB case)

```systemverilog
binsof(paddr) intersect binsof(pwrite.write);
```

âŒ `paddr` = 32-bit address
âŒ `pwrite` = 1-bit control
âŒ No common value domain

This either:

* Creates meaningless bins
* Or never hits
* Or confuses coverage reports

---

## âœ… Use `iff` instead (filtering)

```systemverilog
coverpoint paddr iff (pwrite == 1);
```

âœ” Address is counted
âœ” Only when condition is true
âœ” Exactly what you intended

---

## Cross vs Intersect vs IFF (cheat table)

| Goal                    | Use               |
| ----------------------- | ----------------- |
| Filter samples          | `iff`             |
| Combine signals         | `cross`           |
| AND bins of same signal | `intersect`       |
| Different signals       | âŒ not `intersect` |

